## Import

> **Bulk import tip:** [`tools/generate_import/generate_import.py`](https://github.com/pescobar/terraform-provider-slurm/blob/master/tools/generate_import/generate_import.py)
> queries a running `slurmrestd` instance and generates ready-to-use HCL files plus
> `import {}` blocks for all QOS, accounts, and users in one shot. See its
> [README](https://github.com/pescobar/terraform-provider-slurm/blob/master/tools/generate_import/README.md)
> for usage.

Import an account by its Slurm name:

```bash
tofu import slurm_account.physics physics
```

### Null-preservation after import

Every attribute on `slurm_account` besides `id` and `name` is **Optional-only**
(no `Computed`). The provider only writes such a field into state when it is
already non-null in prior state. This prevents Slurm's inherited defaults —
such as `fairshare = "1"` or a QOS list inherited from the parent account — from
appearing as drift after a fresh import.

After `tofu import`, every Optional field (`fairshare`, `default_qos`,
`allowed_qos`, `parent_account`, etc.) will be null in state, since import only
populates `id` and `name` before the first refresh. A **reconcile apply** is
needed to write config-declared values to Slurm and populate state for any
field your configuration sets — if your configuration leaves a field unset
(matching the null state left by import), there is nothing to reconcile for
that field and `tofu plan` will already be clean without it.

### Standard import workflow

```bash
# Step 1 — import (Optional fields are null in state)
tofu import slurm_account.physics physics

# Step 2 — reconcile apply (writes config-declared values to Slurm)
tofu apply

# Step 3 — verify clean plan (must report no changes)
tofu plan -detailed-exitcode
```

### Removing an attribute from config does not reset it — it stops managing it

**Deleting a field from your configuration is not the same as resetting it to
Slurm's default.** Because every attribute besides `id` and `name` is
Optional-only (see *Null-preservation after import* above), removing it means
"the provider no longer manages this value", **not** "set it back to what Slurm
would assign by default".

Concretely, if you have:

```hcl
resource "slurm_account" "physics" {
  name      = "physics"
  fairshare = "parent"
}
```

and you then delete the `fairshare` line, the account **stays in `parent` mode
in Slurm** — it is *not* reset to the default weight of `1`. On update the
provider simply omits `shares_raw` from its API call (Slurm's upsert leaves any
omitted field untouched), and the null-preservation rule then keeps the field
out of state, so `tofu plan` reports no changes even though Slurm still holds
`parent`. The same applies to `default_qos`, `allowed_qos`, `max_jobs`, the
TRES limits, and `parent_account`: removing any of them stops tracking it,
leaving whatever value is currently live in Slurm in place.

To actually **reset** a field, set it explicitly to the value you want rather
than deleting it — e.g. `fairshare = "1"` to restore the default weight. To
**stop managing** the resource entirely without changing anything in Slurm, use
`tofu state rm`.

### The built-in `root` account can never be deleted

`root` is auto-created the moment a cluster is registered with Slurm
(`sacctmgr add cluster`), and every other account depends on it directly or
via a chain of `parent_account`. There is no valid Slurm administration
workflow that deletes just the root account while the cluster stays
registered, so this provider refuses to do it: any plan that would destroy
a `slurm_account` named `root` — an explicit `tofu destroy`, removing the
resource from configuration, a `for_each` key disappearing, or even a
rename (`name` forces replacement) — fails at `tofu plan` time with
`Error: Refusing to delete protected account "root"`, before any request
reaches `slurmrestd`.

Creating and updating a `slurm_account` named `root` (to manage its own
`fairshare`, `default_qos`, `allowed_qos`, etc.) works normally — only
deletion is blocked. To decommission an entire cluster from the accounting
database, delete the `slurm_cluster` resource instead. To stop managing
`root` with Terraform without deleting it in Slurm, remove it from state
with `tofu state rm` rather than removing it from your configuration.

### `parent_account` drift is not detected once set

`parent_account` has a stricter null-preservation rule than the other Optional
fields: it is only written into state when Slurm's API returns a *non-empty*
parent (in addition to prior state already being non-null). Slurm reports an
account directly under the built-in `root` account as an **empty** parent —
which is indistinguishable, from the provider's point of view, from "not
tracked yet". Consequence: once you've reconciled a non-root `parent_account`,
an out-of-band change that moves the account back under `root` (or a failed
apply that silently leaves it there) is **not detected as drift** — `tofu plan`
will keep reporting no changes even though Slurm no longer matches your
configuration. Verified against a live cluster. There is currently no
workaround short of periodically checking `sacctmgr show account` directly.

### The `Coordinator` role is not supported

Slurm's [user permissions model](https://slurm.schedmd.com/user_permissions.html)
has a second admin-like role beyond `slurm_user`'s `admin_level` (None/
Operator/Administrator): **Coordinator**, a per-account list of usernames
(`sacctmgr add coordinator account=<account> names=<user>`) granting limited
admin rights scoped to that one account and its sub-accounts. This provider
does not manage it — there is no `coordinators` attribute on `slurm_account`,
so it cannot be set, read, or detected as drift through Terraform. Manage
coordinators directly with `sacctmgr` outside this provider if you need them.
See the "Coordinator role" entry in the project's `CLAUDE.md` for what adding
real support would require.
